      if x + - 1 is equal to 0 then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        x is equal to 1 and it is wrong that 1 is an element of A
        falsity holds
      Qed.
      if 0 < x + - 1 then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        x + - 1 is an element of \mathbb{N}
        it is wrong that x + - 1 is an element of A
        Proof:
          x + - 1 + 1 is equal to x and it is wrong that x is an element of A
        Qed.
        x + - 1 is an element of F
        a < x + - 1 or a is equal to x + - 1
        (a + 1 < x + - 1 + 1 or a + 1 is equal to x + - 1 + 1) and x + - 1 + 1 is equal to x
      Qed.
    Qed.
    a < a + 1
    falsity holds
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, if v0 is a real number then for some v1, v1 is an integer and (v1 + - 1 < v0 or v1 + - 1 is equal to v0) and v0 < v1
Proof:
  it is wrong that the thesis holds
  for all v0, if v0 is an integer and v0 is positive and (v0 + - 1 < x or v0 + - 1 is equal to x) then (v0 < x or v0 is equal to x)
  n is an integer and n < x
  A is a class and (if \mathbb{N} is a set then A is a set) and for all v0, v0 is an element of A iff (v0 is an element of \mathbb{N} and v0 is an object and (n + v0 + - 1 < x or n + v0 + - 1 is equal to x))
  A is equal to \mathbb{N}
  Proof:
    A is a subclass of \mathbb{N}
    1 is an element of A
    for all v0, if v0 is an element of A then v0 + 1 is an element of A
    Proof:
      i is an element of A
      n + i + - 1 is equal to n + i + - 1 and (n + i + - 1 < x or n + i + - 1 is equal to x) and (n + i + 1 + - 1 is equal to n + i and (n + i < x or n + i is equal to x))
      i + 1 is an element of A
    Qed.
  Qed.
  x + 1 is an upper bound of \mathbb{Z}
  Proof:
    j is an integer
    j < x + 1 or j is equal to x + 1
    Proof:
      if j < n or j is equal to n then the thesis holds
      n < j
      i is an integer and i is positive and j is equal to n + i
      i is an element of A
      (n + i + - 1 < x or n + i + - 1 is equal to x) and j is equal to n + i and (n + i < x + 1 or n + i is equal to x + 1)
    Qed.
  Qed.
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem (1_20_a):
  for all v0, if v0 is a real number then (if 0 < v0 then for all v1, if v1 is a real number then for some v2, v2 is an integer and v2 is positive and v1 < v2 \cdot v0)
Proof:
  a is an integer and y \cdot 1/ x < a
  n is an integer and n is positive and a < n
  y \cdot 1/ x < n and y \cdot 1/ x \cdot x < n \cdot x and y \cdot 1/ x \cdot x is equal to y
Qed.

Theorem (1_20_b):
  for all v0, for all v1, if v0 is a real number and v1 is a real number then (if v0 < v1 then for some v2, v2 is an element of \mathbb{Q} and v0 < v2 and v2 < v1)
Proof:
  0 < y + - x
  n is an integer and n is positive and 1 < n \cdot y + - x
  Proof:
    z is equal to y + - x
  Qed.
  m is an integer and (m + - 1 < n \cdot x or m + - 1 is equal to n \cdot x) and n \cdot x < m
  Proof:
    z is equal to n \cdot x
  Qed.
  n \cdot x < m and m is equal to m + - 1 + 1 and (m + - 1 + 1 < n \cdot x + 1 or m + - 1 + 1 is equal to n \cdot x + 1) and n \cdot x + 1 < n \cdot x + n \cdot y + - x and n \cdot x + n \cdot y + - x is equal to n \cdot x + y + - x and n \cdot x + y + - x is equal to n \cdot y
  Proof:
    z is equal to y + - x
  Qed.
  0 < n and x is equal to n \cdot x \cdot 1/ n and n \cdot x \cdot 1/ n < m \cdot 1/ n and m \cdot 1/ n < n \cdot y \cdot 1/ n and n \cdot y \cdot 1/ n is equal to y
  p is equal to m \cdot 1/ n
  p is an element of \mathbb{Q} and x < p and p < y
Qed.

